  "doc_id": "6867",
  "text": "Circulating insulin reaches the NAc and diet-induced obesity is accompanied by chronic elevations in circulating insulin [CITATION_1] . In addition, obesity has been associated with a reduction of cognitive-enhancing effects of intra-nasal insulin in humans see (see [CITATION_2] for review) and impairments in hippocampal glutamatergic plasticity [CITATION_3] . Therefore, we predicted that chronic elevations in endogenous insulin produced by high-fat diet-induced obesity may blunt insulin's ability to enhance NAc excitatory transmission. For this set of studies, adult male rats were given free access to 60 % high-fat diet in the home cage for a total of 8 weeks, while controls had free access to standard lab chow (13% fat). As expected, high-fat diet resulted in significant increases in fasted plasma insulin levels ( Figure 6A ; two-tailed unpaired t-test t 26 =3.65, p=0.001; chow N=13, high-fat N=15) and fat mass compared to controls (Figure 6B ; two-tailed unpaired t-test t 26 =6.82, p<0.0001). We next examined the effect of bath application of 30 nM and 100 nM on eEPSC amplitude in slices from high-fat (2), thereby causing disinhibition of presynaptic glutamate release (3). B) Average eEPSC amplitude in the presence of the opioid receptor antagonist (-)-naloxone (1 µM ) before and after bath application of insulin (30 nM). C) Average PP ratio in the presence of (-)-naloxone (1 µM ) before and after bath application of insulin (30 nM). D) Average PP ratio before and after bath application of (-)-naloxone (1 µM ) alone. E) Average PP ratio at baseline (BL), and after insulin (30 nM) in the absence or presence of (-)-naloxone (1 µM ). F) Average PP ratio in the presence of (+)-naloxone (1 µM ) before and after bath application of insulin (30 nM). Example traces are shown within each panel. Statistical differences were determined by two-way RM ANOVA comparing baseline and treatment conditions (B), two-tailed paired t-tests (C, D, F), and one-way ANOVA followed by Sidaks multiple comparisons post-test (E); * = p < 0.05. diet and control rats. Similar to results above, 30 nM insulin increased eEPSC amplitude, whereas 100 nM insulin decreased it in recordings from controls ( Figure 6C circles; two-way RM ANOVA main effect insulin: F (2,8) =5.17, p=0.04; N=5,3). In contrast, in MSNs from high-fat rats 30 nM insulin did not significantly alter eEPSC amplitude, while significant decreases induced by 100 nM insulin persisted ( Figure 6C squares; two-way RM ANOVA main effect insulin: F (2,10) =8.74, p=0.01; BL vs. 30 nM; main effect of insulin: F (1,5) =2.86, p=0.15; BL vs. 100 nM; main effect of insulin: F (1,5) =8.58, p=0.03; N=6,5) . These data are consistent with the idea that physiological shifts in circulating insulin secondary to diet-induced obesity impact neural insulin sensitivity (see also, [CITATION_4] .",
